SIMPLE: jurisdiction
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Jurisdiction
<hw>Ju`ris*dic"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>jurisdictio</ets>; <ets>jus</ets>, <ets>juris</ets>, right, law +
<ets>dictio</ets> a saying, speaking: cf. OF. <ets>jurisdiction</ets>,
F. <ets>juridiction</ets>. See <er>Just</er>, <pos>a.</pos>, and
<er>Diction</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>The legal power, right, or
authority of a particular court to hear and determine causes, to try
criminals, or to execute justice; judicial authority over a cause or
class of causes; <as>as, certain suits or actions, or the cognizance of
certain crimes, are within the <ex>jurisdiction</ex> of a particular
court, that is, within the limits of its authority or
commission</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The authority of a sovereign power to govern or
legislate; the right of making or enforcing laws; the power or right of
exercising authority.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To live exempt⟦br⟧
From Heaven's high <qex>jurisdiction</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You wrought to be a legate; by which power⟦br⟧
You maim'd the <qex>jurisdiction</qex> of all bishops.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Sphere of authority; the limits within which any
particular power may be exercised, or within which a government or a
court has authority.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Jurisdiction</xex>, in its most general sense, is
the power to make, declare, or apply the law. When confined to the
<xex>judiciary department</xex>, it is what we denominate the
<xex>judicial power</xex>, the right of administering justice through
the laws, by the means which the laws have provided for that purpose.
<xex>Jurisdiction</xex> is limited to place or territory, to persons, or
to particular subjects.</note> <rj><au>Duponceau.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Jurisdictional</ent>⟦br⟧
